</P>
<P>
 Throneberry tales: Exploits of the hapless 1962 Mets, and especially the late 
Marv Throneberry, never fade away. George Vecsey, New York Times columnist, 
recently recalled one of his favorites: 
</P>
<P>
 "There was the day that Marv hit a two-out triple with the bases loaded but 
was called out for missing first. Even though nearly everyone in the Mets' 
dugout saw Marv miss the base, Casey Stengel, the manager, started arguing with 
the first base umpire anyway. 
</P>
<P>
 "During the exchange, another umpire walked over and said, 'Casey, I hate to 
tell you this, but he also missed second.' " 
</P>
