<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHUTTLE ASTRONAUTS MEASURE GROWTH OF THEIR SPINES IN SPACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Columbia's astronauts measured their spines Tuesday to understand the effects 
of space travel and logged time on an exercise bike as the shuttle's two-week 
mission began to wind down. 
</P>
<P>
 Richard Hieb and Dr. Chiaki Mukai measured each other's backbone with an 
ultrasound-imaging machine. 
</P>
<P>
 Like all astronauts, Hieb and Mukai have grown a few inches in space because 
the spine stretches in zero gravity. They have measured their heights every day 
in orbit -- Tuesday was the 11th day of a 14-day flight -- and kept a record of 
back pain, a common ailment among astronauts in orbit. 
</P>
<P>
 Flabby muscles also are a side effect of space travel, which is the reason for 
all the cycling. 
</P>
<P>
 "I plan to ride for about 8,000 miles," Hieb said, referring to the distance 
covered by Columbia, not his feet. "It should take me about 30 minutes." 
</P>
<P>
 The shuttle is due to land at the space center Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
