<HEADLINE>
<P>
A REAL CATCH-22: TOO MANY FISH FOR ONE BOAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAIME ABDO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two men were plucked from the ocean 14 miles off Dana Point on Tuesday after 
their fishing boat sank, apparently because they had caught too many fish and 
put them all at one end, Coast Guard officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 "They had too many fish and the tail end went awash," Petty Officer Fransico 
Lopez said."The boat went under -- I guess taking all the fish with it unless 
they stuffed fish in their pockets." 
</P>
<P>
 Men and fish were found floating when the Coast Guard arrived at 6:10 p.m.  
</P>
<P>
 Ron Cochran, 29, of Irvine, owner of the 21-foot boat Ponga , and Darrel 
Beach, 30, of Redondo Beach, made an SOS call at 5:15 p.m. and said the boat 
was taking on water. Within a few minutes after the Coast Guard and two 
helicopters arrived at 6:10 p.m., it had sunk. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was engulfed rather quickly," Lopez said.  
</P>
<P>
 "There was no way to know how many fish they had on board, but it is our 
impression that there were too many fish for that size vessel," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Lopez said the two men, who were shark fishing, were found on the bow of boat 
but then jumped into the water as it capsized. A helicopter lifted the two from 
the water. A Viking Serenade cruise ship also arrived and offered its help. 
</P>
<P>
 Neither fisherman was injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
