<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: SYLMAR; SUPERVISORS AWARD DAM-REPAIR CONTRACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TRACEY KAPLAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Eager to fix damage caused by the Northridge earthquake before the rainy 
season begins, the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors on Tuesday voted to 
ignore the normal contract bidding process and pay an experienced engineering 
firm $400,000 to design the repair of the Pacoima Dam.  
</P>
<P>
 The 370-foot-tall dam in the San Gabriel Mountains above Sylmar sustained 
$4.9-million damage in the quake, 97% of which will be paid for by the Federal 
Emergency Management Agency, county officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 The quake created a two-inch gap between the top of the dam and a massive 
concrete block connecting it to the canyon wall. It also caused that concrete 
connection to move about half an inch downstream relative to the dam's crest. 
As a precaution, the reservoir pool behind the dam is being kept at one-seventh 
of its capacity, said Jim Noyes, deputy director of the county Department of 
Public Works. 
</P>
<P>
 The supervisors awarded the contract to the firm of Morrison Knudsen of San 
Francisco, which also designed $3 million in dam repairs necessary after the 
1971 Sylmar quake. TRACEY KAPLAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
