<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTY SEEKING MORE PARK RESERVE OFFICERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TRACEY KAPLAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Alarmed by recent attacks on lifeguards at a public swimming pool in Watts, 
Los Angeles County supervisors Tuesday moved to bolster security in the parks 
by making it more attractive for volunteers to become park police reserve 
officers. 
</P>
<P>
 Budget cutbacks and mounting violence have forced the county to rely heavily 
on reserves, a trend that is expected to continue, said Rodney E. Cooper, 
director of the Department of Parks and Recreation. 
</P>
<P>
 Currently, the county has 69 sworn officers on its park police force and 54 
reserve officers. The reserves, who are qualified as peace officers and carry 
guns, donate 20 hours a week each to the county. 
</P>
<P>
 To attract volunteers to the park police force, the board, without discussion, 
authorized the parks department to purchase disability income insurance for the 
reserve officers. In the past, injured reserve officers received no benefits. 
Under the new policy, injured reservists will receive a weekly disability 
payment of $250 for up to two years. 
</P>
<P>
 The insurance will cost the county only $1,100 annually for all reservists, a 
token amount that was not previously allocated because parks officials did not 
want to single out reserve officers from among the more than 5,000 park 
volunteers, said Park Police Chief Paul Zrofsky. None of the others are covered 
by disability insurance. 
</P>
<P>
 But increasing violence in the county's 129 parks, including the recent 
attacks on lifeguards at Will Rogers Park, has lent a new urgency to the need 
to increase the number of reserve officers, Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
 Last month, six lifeguards were injured in gang-related attacks at the public 
pool. After numerous complaints about new fees imposed on pool users this 
summer, Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke raised more than $65,000 in 
corporate and private donations to eliminate the fees in her district. 
</P>
<P>
 But plans to obtain the insurance were in the works even before the recent 
attacks, Cooper said. Budget cutbacks have left the department 14 officers 
short, making it "essential that we recruit more reserves," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Reservists must pass a background check and psychological exam, and complete a 
34-week-long, part-time training program in either Santa Clarita or East Los 
Angeles, Zrofsky said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
